    reflection:'After decades of life experience, it\'s easy to accumulate a certain confidence in your own knowledge — and equally easy for that confidence to curdle into pride that makes younger people feel small rather than built up. Paul\'s short but pointed contrast matters here: knowledge alone inflates, but love genuinely builds people up. As you mentor, ask yourself whether your teaching leaves the other person feeling capable and encouraged, or simply reminded of how much they still don\'t know. The goal of wisdom shared should always be edification, not demonstration of your own superiority.',
    wisdom:['Knowledge without love tends toward pride, not helpfulness.','The goal of teaching should be building others up, not demonstrating superiority.','Check whether your correction leaves people encouraged or diminished.'],
    questions:['After your last piece of advice to someone, did they walk away feeling built up or diminished?'],
