    reflection:'There is a peculiar loneliness in grieving abroad — no relatives dropping by with food, no wake to sit through with neighbors, just you, a small room, and news from home that arrived on a screen. Paul reminds us that God\'s comfort is not tied to a place or a community\'s presence, though those things help. It is the character of God Himself, portable, given wherever you are, so that later you might comfort others who carry the same solitary grief. Your years of mourning alone overseas were not wasted; they were quietly preparing you to be a comforter for the next OFW who receives that same terrible phone call far from home.',
