    reflection:'Some losses arrive suddenly — a flood, a fire, an accident back home — while you are thousands of miles away, powerless to help, learning the details secondhand through a shaky phone call. The guilt of not being there can feel as heavy as the loss itself. Isaiah\'s promise was written for exiles who had already lost their homeland once and feared losing everything again. God does not promise the waters will never rise. He promises to be in them with you — and with those you love — even the waters you could not physically stand in beside them. His presence does not require your presence to be real for the ones you love.',
    wisdom:['You cannot always be physically present, but God always is','Guilt over distance during disaster is understandable but not deserved','God\'s presence with loved ones never depended on yours'],
    questions:['Is there a crisis back home you missed and still carry guilt over — could you name that guilt honestly to God this week?'],
    prayer:'Lord, You were with them in the waters even when I could not be. Release me from guilt I was never meant to carry alone. Amen.',
    act:'Write down the guilt you carry about a crisis you missed, then pray it back to God as an act of release.'
