    reflection:'This was spoken to Joshua as he faced an uncertain future without Moses, his mentor and companion for forty years, now dead. The grief of losing a mentor, a longtime pastor, or a lifelong friend can leave a very similar sense of disorientation — who guides me now, who do I turn to. God\'s answer to Joshua was not to give him a replacement Moses, but to remind him that God Himself had always been the one truly leading, even through Moses. The mentor was a gift, but never the source. As you grieve whoever guided you for decades, take comfort that the true Guide behind them is still present, still going before you, even now.',
    wisdom:['Grieving a mentor is grieving a real gift, but not the ultimate source of guidance','God\'s presence does not end when a human guide is gone','Discouragement after losing a guide is understandable, but not the final word'],
    questions:['Who was a mentor or guide you have lost — could you thank God this week for what He gave through them, and ask for continued guidance now?'],
    prayer:'Lord, thank You for the mentor You gave me for a season. Now guide me directly, as You always have behind the scenes. Amen.',
    act:'Write down three lessons your mentor taught you and thank God specifically for each one this week.'
